3.1

CLT <- function(S, sigma, R) {

  averages <- numeric(R)
  
  for (i in 1:R) {
    samples <- rlnorm(S, 0, sigma)
    averages[i] <- mean(samples)
  }
  
  hist(averages, breaks = 30, main = paste("Histogram of Averages (S =", S, ", sigma =", sigma, ")"),
       xlab = "Averages", col = "pink")
}

3.3

CLT(20, 0.2, 10000)

3.4

CLT(1, 1, 10000)

3.5

CLT(20, 1, 10000)

3.6

CLT(1, 2, 10000)

3.9

When S = 20, the standard deviation = 0.2 looks more normal.

When standard deviation is fixed, more sample tends to make the distribution more normal When sample size is fixed, less standard deviation make function more normal The larger sample size the more normal it looks. While larger sd less normal it looks.

After testing I notice that standard deviation affects skewness more than sample size. If the sd is really small such as 0.1, sample size wont change much of how normal it looks
